AIM:

To create a simple Employee Management module using Spring Core and demonstrate Inversion of Control (IoC) and Dependency Injection (DI) using annotations such as @Component and @Autowired. The application should use BeanFactory to manage beans and store employee data in memory.

PROCEDURE:

Create a simple Spring Core project using Java.

Create a class Employee with attributes:

Employee ID
Employee Name
Department

Create a class EmployeeService and annotate it with @Component to make it a Spring bean.

Use @Autowired to inject the Employee object into the service class (Dependency Injection).

Use BeanFactory to load the Spring configuration and manage beans.

Store employee data in memory using simple variables or a list.

Create a main class to:

Load the Spring container
Get the EmployeeService bean
Add employee details
Display employee details

Run the program and verify that Spring automatically creates and injects the required objects.

CODE:
Employee.java
package com.spring.employee;

import org.springframework.stereotype.Component;

@Component
public class Employee {

    private int empId;
    private String empName;
    private String department;

    public Employee() {
    }

    public int getEmpId() {
        return empId;
    }

    public void setEmpId(int empId) {
        this.empId = empId;
    }

    public String getEmpName() {
        return empName;
    }

    public void setEmpName(String empName) {
        this.empName = empName;
    }

    public String getDepartment() {
        return department;
    }

    public void setDepartment(String department) {
        this.department = department;
    }
}
EmployeeService.java
package com.spring.employee;

import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Component;

@Component
public class EmployeeService {

    @Autowired
    private Employee employee;

    public void addEmployee(int id, String name, String dept) {
        employee.setEmpId(id);
        employee.setEmpName(name);
        employee.setDepartment(dept);
    }

    public void displayEmployee() {
        System.out.println("Employee ID: " + employee.getEmpId());
        System.out.println("Employee Name: " + employee.getEmpName());
        System.out.println("Department: " + employee.getDepartment());
    }
}
applicationContext.xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<beans xmlns="http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans"
       xmlns:context="http://www.springframework.org/schema/context"
       xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
       xsi:schemaLocation="
       http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans
       http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans/spring-beans.xsd
       http://www.springframework.org/schema/context
       http://www.springframework.org/schema/context/spring-context.xsd">

    <!-- Enable Annotation Scanning -->
    <context:component-scan base-package="com.spring.employee"/>

</beans>
MainApp.java
package com.spring.employee;

import org.springframework.beans.factory.BeanFactory;
import org.springframework.context.support.ClassPathXmlApplicationContext;

public class MainApp {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        BeanFactory factory =
                new ClassPathXmlApplicationContext("applicationContext.xml");

        EmployeeService service = factory.getBean(EmployeeService.class);

        service.addEmployee(101, "Arun", "IT");
        service.displayEmployee();
    }
}
RESULT:

Thus, a simple Employee Management module was successfully created using Spring Core.
Inversion of Control (IoC) and Dependency Injection (DI) were implemented using @Component and @Autowired annotations.
The BeanFactory container successfully managed the beans, and employee data was stored and displayed in memory using Spring-managed objects.
